Mr Obama announced on Friday that the U.S. would start sending weaponry,
while Britain and France remained concerned that the firepower might 
end up helping anti-democratic extremists linked to Iran and Lebanon's 
Hezbollah militia.

Mr Putin has defended Russia's continuing supply of weapons to Assad's military.

At least 93,000 people have been killed in Syria's conflict since it 
erupted in March 2011, according to a recent U.N. estimate. Millions 
have been displaced.

Mr Obama also said he and Mr Putin, 60, expressed cautious optimism 
about the ability to move forward on a dialogue with Iran after a 
moderate cleric was elected president there.

